<br>
Seven steps to heaven. Points 1 and 2 deal with rogue functionality, specifically with groups in mind. Points 3 and 4 deal with problems with raiding. 5 and 6 deal with wideneing the equipment choices of rogues. 7 is a sort of post script. The step I'd most like to see implemented is step 2.<br>
<br>
1) Assassinate should be like banish summoned. You choose to use it (you have a special button), if the mob is lower level than you it has a reasonable chance of success, the mob insta dies with no xp gain and no loot. Assassinate thus becomes a method of crowd control. It should be massive agro catcher and from behind only, meaning that you likely only get one shot at it and if the monster is a hard hitter a failed assassinate can easily mean death. This prevents it overpowering mezzes. Oh, and its only effective on humanoid (pickpocketable) mobs.<br>
<br>
2) Forget special tendonslicer attacks etc. Just make poisons MUCH simpler to use. <br>
<br>
a) Poisons should have only 2 ingredients; a vial and a poison ingredient. This means that you can make poisons &quot;on the fly&quot; as it were. i.e. you're hunting in random_zone_03 and a poison ingredient drops and you can immediately turn that ingredient into a poison without having to run to the bank to get the right vial or other ingredients, and without logging off to trawl through poison recipes.<br>
<br>
b) There should be only 1 type of vial which is used for ALL poisons, thus ensuring that a rogue can carry enough vials around with him at any one time.<br>
<br>
c) Poison making should be less like a tradeskill and more like any the apply poison skill. You should not have to spend hours sitting in PoK doing combines in order to use a skill that is so central to your class.<br>
<br>
d) The vial must be stackable. The ingredient must be stackable. The poison does not have to be stackable since you make them as and when you need them.<br>
<br>
[The idea is that rogue_01 walks around with 10 stacks of vials in his bag. He gets a group, let's say in PoD. The mobs drop a poison ingredient. As the ingredients drop, he should be able to turn those ingredients into poisons. Being able to do this should NOT require that you are a grandmaster poisoner and should NOT require that you have spent hours farming other ingredients and should NOT require that you can remember what the hell the other ingredients are.]<br>
<br>
NB: for those of you worried that your GM poison making should be devalued, the GM poison item can still summon the vials. Everyone else will have to make vials or buy them at a pp a go. Everyone else will have to carry stacks of vials around with them. GM poison makers will not. BUT THERE SHOULD STILL ONLY BE ONE TYPE OF VIAL.<br>
<br>
3) Give rogues (and possibly other melees) an improved parry AA which gives you a much more effective parry that ONLY funtions against ripostes.<br>
<br>
4) Give rogues (and possibily other melees) an improved resistance AA or discipline which dramatically increases AE resistance for a relatively long period of time (one or two mins or more?).<br>
<br>
5) Improve availability of good daggers (not the best daggers, I'm thinking around 12, 13, 14 or 15 damage) AND make ragebringer range slot equipable. Making ragebringer equipable in range slot means that those rogues who can't get hold of other 41 haste items can still play around with their offhand slot. At the moment I wield a decent (14-20) piercer in mainhand that I'm happy with and ragebringer offhand and I absolutly cannot replace either. If ragebringer was range slot equipable, I could play around with my offhand a lot more, perhaps get *gasp* a slashing weapon, or something with a handy proc =)<br>
<br>
6) Make throwing equal to archery. It isn't so hard. Insert some range slot items that summon very good throwing items that have high enough damage to be comparable with archery. Sort of like the bag that summons shissar fangs. Some of these items should be tradeskillable, meaning that they will be acquireable to those that aren't high end raiding.<br>
<br>
7) Review damage. If all the above points 1 to 6 were implemented, I'm not certain that rogues would need more damage increases. But it's worth a look.<br>
<br>
Shackleton<br>
