<br>
2)  Poisons.  Honestly, I think most are fine but too weak.  The dex debuff poisons from both old and new world poisons are great... they don't do a ton on their own but they stack with cripple, making them nice for raids.  They can't land on everything... you need to pick your targets well (on my guild page I'm making a list now of targets I can land poisons on) but they have an effect.  The new resist debuff poison is also great... lowers all resists by 10 (not that amazing) but stacks with everything, so that's helpful.  The damage poisons stink though... who wants to farm for hours to get a few 555 DD one shot poisons when I can backstab for up to 2056 on a double hit?  These need to do a lot more damage.  I'd also change the resists on one shot points... make them -50 poison check or something, so they work when you want them to work, but only once.  The slow and snare poisons also need to last a lot longer... it's really sad when you land a 50% slow 50% snare poison, and it lasts for 1 tick.  But I do like that it's a hard to use tradeskill, with some benefits up top.  <br>
<br>
PoP poisons need to last longer though... they don't work in exp situations at all.  I mean come on, the last batch of oozing iritation I made cost me 600pp with failures.  With 10 charges of 15 minutes each, that's 4pp per minute, not including time spent to combine and farm.  Now compare that to a shaman casting avatar, the component version, which is I think about 15pp for 6 minutes, so 2-3pp per minute for more damage with no farming time, or a cleric casting Virtue, which is cheap as all hell.  Come on, risk vs. reward!<br>
<br>
One easy solution for PoP poisons, of course, would be questable endless decanters for various poisons.  We've got part of the quest already... require the black marble mortar and pestle (which is currently costly and useless) and the master sketch (god that was a lot of work just to be able to make RoI and DoD), and make endless PoP style poisons a reality after an epic style quest.<br>
<br>
3.  Bah, repostes hurt... don't get hit by them.  That's where skill is needed.<br>
<br>
4.  I've actually thought giving rogues an Uncanny Dodge style ability (D&amp;D rip off, I know), that would let us apply our dodge skill to AoEs and Damage Shields.  It would make rogues far more viable in PvP (which they could sure use... it's embarasing to be beaten by AFK druids, okay?) as well as letting us get into the fight in PoP encounters where currently all we can do is sit back and shoot with a bow (go go 30 DPS).  Monks should have this one too.  I'd imagine it would let a person dodge about 40% of them at top level... not enough to allow you to ignore AoEs (which would trivialize high end content) but enough to make it worthwhile to let the rogues fight.  <br>
<br>
5.  Yes, rogue itemization needs work at high level.  It's fine at this level, actually... but needs work farther up.  But the Ragebringer Curse is tough.  Make it rangeable and rogue can no longer use range items, it'll just move the same problem to a different slot.  Best thing I can think of is a few rogue only very tough quests that result in items with Seething Fury, which go in other slots, and then not let the effects stack with other Seething Furies.  That would let rogues get Ragebringer out of that slot and use better ratio weapons again.  As it is, we can't bank our epic until we've got Bloodbath or better for our offhand, and that's a little much.<br>
<br>
6.  Throwing shouldn't equal archery... they are two different skills, and should remain as such.  But it would be nice for throwing to have SOME advantage of archery for rogues, and have a few niceities for monks as well.  Let's face it, we're given fun throwing skills (250 throwing, crits and deadly strikes), but bows still beat throwers across the board, except in the case of the Shissar bag.  Solution:  allow the use of throwing weapons in the ammo slot while another range item is in range slot.  This gives throwing a unique advantage... you're not restricted to using a bow.  Still much less damage and range, but it means you could have better stats in that slot.  Endless bandolier would be nice, of course, as would the two other rogue abilities that are in game but unavailable (use alt act # to find them), namely quick throw and I believe long throw.  But bow damage and range should be better... throwers should just have something to make 'em useful.<br>
<br>
7)  Rogues bring damage to the table.  That's what we do, and it's nearly all we do right now.  If we have other things to bring, okay that's fine, but Damage and a little CR is all we got right now, and when we get outdamaged by rangers beastlords mages and wizards, all of whom bring many other things, we have a problem.  Yes, we need either more damage or more utility.  SoS was a good start on rogue utility, though.<br>
